<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-541-295  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 541 295.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Oct 22 1990 n323 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T switches gears on telcos. (reportedly subverting localexchange carriers' plans to offer high-speed switched services )</TITLE><AUTHOR>Foley, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ATandamp;T, in an abrupt about-face, has decided that its software for384K-bps switched data service is proprietary and will not shareit with several telephone companies that had hoped to offer thehigh-speed services to their business customers.andP;  The software,which runs on the ATandamp;T 4ESS Tandem switches widely used by Belloperating companies and independent telephone companies, allowsdevelopment of services users can pay for on a per-use basisrather than by leasing dedicated connections.andP;  Users say ATandamp;T hadpreviously offered to make the 4ESS software available totelephone companies, but claims it never promised that anyonecould buy the software.andP;  ATandamp;T's move comes at a critical time forthe telcos, who say customer interest in switched 384K-bps serviceis growing rapidly.andP;  ATandamp;T now plans to offer 'trials,' but someare skeptical that its plans can be implemented quickly.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (customer relations).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Telephone CompaniesSwitchingData CommunicationsCustomer RelationsProprietary SystemsCommunications SoftwareTelecommunications Services.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>